## Decomposable Norm Correction

A sidecar check found that the standard Haagerup/Wittstock decomposable norm is **not** `1` for every unital positive decomposable map. The transpose on `M_n` is unital, positive, trace-preserving, and decomposable, but its standard decomposable norm is `n`.

The decomposable `alpha=1` theorem should therefore be phrased using an explicit CP+coCP decomposition

`Phi = Phi_0 + Psi_0 o tau`

with bounded CP pieces. For a unital map this component control is automatic from any such decomposition because `Phi_0(1)+Psi_0(1)=1`, hence `||Phi_0||_cb, ||Psi_0||_cb <= 1`. See `agent-B/notes/subagent-decomposable-norm.md`.

I recorded the remaining proof route and obstacles in
`agent-B/notes/decomposable-alpha1-route.md`. The key issue is that the CP and
coCP summands are not individually unital or almost idempotent; the proof needs
a single doubled/universal-envelope two-hole calculation controlled by
`||Phi^2-Phi||`.

Update 2026-06-02: the naive doubled/lifted route is not automatically
controlled.
If `Phi=Cj` is the decomposable factorization through a doubled/opposite
algebra, then `F=jC` satisfies `F^2-F=j((Phi-I)C)`, and
`||Phi^2-Phi||` does not control this on all of `C(D)`. There is even a
commutative stochastic example in the exact doubled form with `Cj` exactly
idempotent but `||jCjC-jC||=1`. See
`agent-B/notes/decomposable-doubling-obstruction.md`. Thus any `O(eta)`
decomposable proof needs an additional dilation-compatible hypothesis or a
direct CP/coCP two-hole identity.

There is a clean conditional positive result: if a dilation-compatible model
can be chosen so that `F=jC` is genuinely UCP and
`||F^2-F||_cb<=eta`, then Kitaev's UCP theorem applied to `F` restricts along
the Jordan embedding and gives the desired `O(eta)` algebraic bridge for
`Phi=Cj`. This is recorded at
`agent-B/notes/decomposable-dilation-compatible-theorem.md`. The point is that
the UCP lifted-map hypothesis is extra; it is not automatic for a general
CP+coCP decomposition.

Sartre sidecar independently stressed this: a bad CP+coCP decomposition of the
exact depolarizing projection on `M_2` has `eta=0` but nonzero off-diagonal
universal-envelope defect `||Phi F-F||>=eps/2`. So a proof cannot use an
arbitrary supplied decomposition without either selecting a compatible one or
showing intrinsic cancellation. See
`agent-B/notes/subagent-decomposable-alpha1-stress.md`.

## Factorization Rounding Obstruction

The algebraic bridge does not yet give exact UP factor maps. After Layer 1, the
obvious maps are `Delta_0=inclusion o v` and `Upsilon_0=v^{-1} o P`. They
factorize `P` algebraically, but `P` is only approximately positive.

McClintock found that a generic dimension-free `O(epsilon)` repair theorem is
false for finite-dimensional JB targets. The counterexample uses spin factors
`J=R oplus R^m` and maps from `ell_infty^{2m}` that are `epsilon`-positive but
at distance at least `sqrt(epsilon)` from every positive unital map. Composing
with a diagonal conditional expectation gives the same obstruction for domain
`B(C^{2m})_sa`.

Therefore, to keep the bridge exponent in an exact UP factorization theorem, we
need one of:

- a concrete Layer 1 output plus a comparison argument with a canonical
  positive conditional expectation;
- near-positive projection stability, giving a positive idempotent close to
  `P`;
- positivity built into the Layer 1 output from the start;
- extra hypotheses excluding the spin-factor negative-variation obstruction.

If we use only black-box approximate-positive repair, a square-root loss is
unavoidable in this level of generality. I recorded the issue in
`agent-B/notes/factorization-positivity-rounding.md` and
`agent-B/notes/subagent-positivity-rounding.md`.

Update: I formalized the near-positive-projection route as
`agent-B/theory/theorem-C-conditional-factorization.md`. Assuming the
projection-stability theorem

```text
delta-positive unital idempotent P with ||P||<=1+delta
  => dist(P, positive unital idempotents) <= C sqrt(delta),
```

an almost-idempotent UP map `Phi` has exact UP factor maps through
`J=E(B(H)_sa)`, where `E` is the nearby positive idempotent. The maps are
`Delta` equal to inclusion and `Upsilon=E`; they satisfy
`Upsilon Delta=id_J`,
`||Delta Upsilon-Phi||<=C sqrt(eta)`, and
`Upsilon(Delta(x)oDelta(y))=x*y` exactly for the Effros-Stormer product on
`J`. Thus the remaining unproved ingredient on this route is precisely
projection stability, not the factorization step.

Latest theorem-C hardening: I patched
`agent-B/theory/theorem-C-conditional-factorization.md` to spell out the
real-to-complex invocation of Effros-Stormer. A unital positive idempotent
`E:B(H)_sa->B(H)_sa` extends complex-linearly by
`E_C(a+ib)=E(a)+iE(b)` to a unital positive projection on `B(H)`, since
positivity is tested on positive self-adjoint inputs. Effros-Stormer applies
to `E_C`, and restricting back to the self-adjoint range gives the real
special JB product `x*y=E(x o y)` and inherited order-unit cone
`J cap B(H)_+`.
I also made the positivity of the factor maps explicit: `Delta` is the
inclusion and sends `J_+=J cap B(H)_+` into `B(H)_+`; `Upsilon=E` sends
`B(H)_+` into `J_+` because `E` is positive and idempotent.
The theorem-C proof now verifies that this inherited cone is exactly the JB
positive cone for the Effros-Stormer product. If `x=y*y=E(y o y)`, then `x` is
ambient-positive. Conversely, if `z in J cap B(H)_+`, then with
`m=||z||`, the ambient inequality `0<=z<=m1` gives `||m1-z||<=m` in the
inherited norm; the unital JB norm criterion implies `z` is JB-positive.
Thus theorem-C genuinely gives positive maps through the special JB cone.

## Layer 1 Quantitative Stability Obligations

I sharpened the Layer 1 review in
`agent-B/notes/layer1-quantitative-obligations-v0.2.md`. The key point is that
Kitaev's error-reduction lemma uses more than qualitative `H^2=0`: it uses a
diagonal represented as a probability average of norm-one elements, hence with
projective tensor norm `1`. The Jordan analogue must provide the same kind of
dimension-free bounded homotopy in the order-unit norm.

Concretely, Agent A's route needs:

- an explicit Jordan cochain homotopy/right inverse to `d^1`;
- a universal norm bound for matrix factors, spin factors, direct sums, and the
  Albert factor;
- a bounded projection/homotopy controlling approximate cocycles, not just exact
  cocycles;
- explicit approximate-module error estimates because the codomain is only an
  epsilon-JB algebra;
- positive/concrete output if the result is to imply exact UP factorization.

Haar averaging over `Aut(B)` has norm `1` as an averaging projection, but that
alone is not a right inverse to the Jordan coboundary. The inverse on the
non-invariant cochain components is where dimension/rank dependence could
enter.

Latest literature check:
`agent-B/notes/known-jstar-stability-literature-check.md` records that the
local Baak--Moslehian J*-homomorphism stability paper does not prove our
Layer 1 theorem. It stabilizes maps between already exact J*-algebras under
global Hyers/Rassias scaling hypotheses; it does not perturb an epsilon-JB
product on an order-unit space to an exact JB algebra. Chu--Russo/Penico
gives qualitative cohomological triviality, but not the needed
dimension-free order-unit-norm homotopy.

